    <h1>About</h1>
    <p>
      <i>The Outpost</i> is where I share my journey mapping the world. As an aspiring land surveyor, I write about what
      I learn, hoping to share this with others. I also explore new places and create 3D models, meshes and maps with my
      drone.
    </p>
    <h2>What does <i>The Outpost</i> aspire to do that is unique?</h2>
    <p>
      <i>The Outpost</i> is working towards providing bespoke and detailed surveying products beyond the AutoCAD file
      and plat. When we survey land, we create the standard survey you need, but we include more. The traditional
      methods producing lines and bearings are important, and this will live alongside 3D models of features, meshes,
      and ortho-imagery of the area. Most importantly, we provide an interactive web application to view your map, and
      all of the data will also be availible for download.
    </p>
    <h2>Who am I?</h2>
    <p>
      Creating maps has been both my hobby and job for about 10 years. I began by studying Geographic Information
      Science at Oregon State University. After studying Computer Science at Portland State University, I wanted to
      apply my programming skills to a craft I enjoy. I collected and poured over road maps ever since I was a child, so
      learning GIS seemed like a sensible path forward. One piece of advice I took to heart was that software
      engineering is a rewarding career, but it is even more enjoyable if you can apply it to something domain specific.
    </p>
    <p>
      After school, I went on to work as a software developer at SpatialDev, a GIS software consulting company out of
      Seattle, WA. There I built interactive web and mobile applications. After a few years, I went to work at Apple
      Maps. At Apple, I worked extensively with OpenStreetMap data, ingesting and editing the data into Apple's map of
      the world. I then continued onto the team that built their internal map editing application. My team's application
      is used at an industrial scale by map editors and analysts to produce the map data you experience in Apple
      products. I enjoyed discovering how map data works, particularly regarding human editing, automated topological
      correction, and the transformation and conflation of data coming from different sources.
    </p>
    <p>
      I am a licensed FAA Remote Drone Pilot, as well as a certified GIS Professional (GISP). I will be returning to
      school in 2023, attending the University of Maine's Survey Engineering Techology program, working towards becoming
      a licensed land surveyor.
    </p>
