    <h2>Why surveying?</h2>
    <p>
      Having worked on building map data covering the scope of the world's road network, I am now working towards
      becoming a licensend land surveyor.
    </p>
    <p>
      As I grow older, I want to spend more time outside. The draw of a map is to see what we know is there, and
      explore--find something new and see the world from a different angle.
    </p>
    <p>
      Land Surveying is the profession that embraces this pursuit. A survey is a map that is geared towards Civil
      Engineering and legal documents, such as land deeds. Here it is essential to be exact with our measurements, and
      our research and observations need to state our level of confidence, accuracy, and precision. If any changes to
      the land are to be made, such as construction, it is important that the observations of the surveyor are correct.
    </p>
    <p>
      The purpose of the map dictates what <i>correct</i> means. For example, it is reasonable to use OpenStreetMap data
      for auto navigation where sections of rural roads are off by several meters. It is close enough for successful
      vehicle navigation. On the other hand, when this section of road needs to be paved, or a bridge is to built, the
      location of the stakes for the pavers needs to be more precise. Anything that involves construction requires a lot
      of time and energy, and this makes detail and accuracy essential. For this to happen, someone needs to be out
      in the field to make the needed measurements.
    </p>
